        'Mongolian': 'The mapping for the Ali Gali orthography for Mongolian was referenced from the Wikipedia article. The mapping is not yet verified. If you have any feedback on the mapping, forms of the letters used and an appropriate font that could be used, please send it to vinodh@virtualvinodh.com',
        'GunjalaGondi': 'Gunjala Gondi does not have an explicit visible Virama. It also lacks /ñ/ and /ṇ/. When these phonemes occur in their vowelless forms to nasalize their corresponding consonant series, they are replaced by the Anusvara.',
        'Soyombo': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/ & /j/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA & DZA respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals</i> options, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha by default uses Sanskrit-specific orthography. However, Mongolian/Tibetan specific orthographic practices can be enabled as required. <ul> <li> Use final letters to encode word-final vowelless consonants <br/> samyak asmad : <span class="soyombo">𑪁𑩴𑪙𑩻𑪋 𑩐𑪁𑪙𑩴𑪍</span> <br/> There are final forms for 11 consonants. <br/> ak ag aṅ ad an ab am ar al aś as : <span class="soyombo">𑩐𑪋 𑩐𑪊 𑩐𑪌 𑩐𑪍 𑩐𑪎 𑩐𑪏 𑩐𑪐 𑩐𑪑 𑩐𑪒 𑩐𑪓 𑩐𑪔</span><li> Use initial-forms for /ra/, /la/ and /sa/. <br/> rka lka ska : <span class="soyombo">𑪆𑩜 𑪇𑩜 𑪉𑩜</span> (Tibetan) : <span class="soyombo">𑩼𑪙𑩜 𑩽𑪙𑩜 𑪁𑪙𑩜</span> (Sanskrit) <li> Convert spaces into Tshegs. pra co da yāt :  <span class="soyombo">𑩰𑪙𑩼𑪚𑩵𑩖𑪚𑩭𑪚𑩻𑩛𑩫</span></ul> Since, Soyombo does not have a visible Virama, certain Sanskrit words that do end in a consonants cannot be accurately expressed (and has to be contextually inferrred). One way to overcome this is to use Tshegs and divide the word into indidvidual syllables (similar to Tibetan). /parama/ as <span class="soyombo">𑩰𑪚𑩼𑪚𑩴</span> (pa^ra^ma) but /param/ as <span class="soyombo">𑩰𑪚𑩼𑩴</span> (pa^rama). Or alternatively use Mongolian-final forms. /param/ as <span class="soyombo">𑩰𑩼𑪐</span>.',
        'KhomThai': 'The font used encodes Khom Thai using Thai Unicode characters. In the absence of the font, the text will appear as plain Thai. The font is also specifically aimed for only Pali, therefore, it misses Sanskrit-specific characters that include the independent vowels of /ṛ/, /ṝ/, /ḷ/, /ḹ/, /ai/ and /au/, the dependent vowel signs /ḷ/, /ḹ/ and /au/ and the consonants /ś/ and /ṣ/. They have been approximated to closest possible letter. Traditionally, Khom Thai can express both Sanskrit and Pali.',
        'Mon': 'The Sanskrit characters /ṛ/, /ṝ/, /ḷ/,  /ḹ/, /ś/ and /ṣ/ were directly adopted from the corresponding Burmese characters for the sake of completing the Indic character reportoire.',
        'Shan': 'The Sanskrit characters /ṛ/, /ṝ/, /ḷ/,  /ḹ/, /ś/ and /ṣ/ were directly adopted from the corresponding Burmese characters for the sake of completing the Indic character reportoire.',
        'KhamtiShan': '<b>Numerals</b><br/> Khamti in India use Myanmar numerals instead of Shan numerals. This can be enabled if needed <br/><br/> <b> Khamti /r/ </b><br/> Khamti also has an archaic /r/ <span class="khamtishan">ꩳ</span>. An option can be enabled to use this instead of <span class="khamtishan">ရ</span>.',
        'TaiLaing': '',
        'ZanabazarSquare': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/ & /j/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA, & DZA respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals options</i>, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨐 𑨑 𑨒</span> instead of <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨣 𑨤 𑨥</span>.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha by default uses Sanskrit-specific orthography. However, Mongolian/Tibetan specific orthographic practices can be enabled as required. <ul> <li>Tibetan uses contextual alternatives for post-consonantal /ya/, /ra/, /la/ and /va/, while Sanskrit does not. <br/> kya kra kla kva: <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨋𑩇𑨪 𑨋𑩇𑨫 𑨋𑩇𑨬 𑨋𑩇𑨭 </span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨋𑨻 𑨋𑨼 𑨋𑨽 𑨋𑨾 </span> (Tibetan) <li>The Tibetan orthography employs a repha-like character for pre-consonantal /ra/. <br/> rka : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨫𑩇𑨋</span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨺𑨋</span> (Tibetan)<li> Sanskrit orthography also uses different signs for /ai/ and /au/ as opposed to Mongolian. <br/>ai au kai kau : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨀𑨄𑨊 𑨀𑨆𑨊 𑨋𑨄𑨊 𑨋𑨆𑨊</span> (Sanskrit) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨀𑨇 𑨀𑨈 𑨋𑨇 𑨋𑨈</span> (Mongolian) <li> Mongolian orthography uses a dot to suppress the inherent vowel instead of a Virama. <br/>ak: <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨀𑨬𑨳</span> (Mongolian) : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨀𑨬𑨴</span> (Tibetan/Sanskrit) <li> Convert spaces into Tshegs. pra co da yāt : <span class="zanabazarsquare">𑨞𑩇𑨫𑩁𑨣𑨆𑩁𑨛𑩁𑨪𑨊𑨙𑨴</span> </ul> These alternate forms can be chosen by selecting the appropriate checkboxes in the ouput section.',
        'Avestan': 'Avestan has a tradition of being transliterated into Gujarati and Devanagari. This has been followed more or less. As such, Avestan fricatives have been mapped to Indian aspirates. Avestan vowels that do not have Indic equivalents have been mapped to /æ/, /ǣ/ and /ô/. <span class="avestan">𐬃</span> is mapped to /ā_o/. There are additional Avestan consonants that do not fit into the Indic scheme above. In such cases, they are mapped to the the closest Nukta-ted Indic counterparts. <span class="avestan">𐬝 𐬡 𐬤 𐬲</span> (right to left) :  ẗ v̈ ṅ̈ z̈ (left to right).<br/><br/>At non-initial positions /ya/ is represented by <span class="avestan">𐬌𐬌</span>. Similarly, at non-initial positions, /va/ is represented by <span class="avestan">𐬎𐬎</span>. And, /āṃ/ becomes <span class="avestan">𐬅</span><br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Avestan output in accordance to the Avestan orthographic conventions. <br/> <ul><li>Contextual placement of <span class="avestan">𐬝 𐬲 𐬧</span><li>/kh/ and /ś/ before /y/ are replaced by the palatalized <span class="avestan">𐬒 𐬳</span> respectively.</ul> ',
        'Balinese': 'Aksharamukha places the repha automatically on the preceding consonants. /karma/ : <a span="balinese">ᬓᬃᬫ</span>',
        'Assamese': 'Khanda /ta/ is formed automatically depending on the text. It is used word-finally and at positions where /t/ does not form conjoining conjuncts. /tat/ : <span class="bengali">তৎ</span> & /utpāda/ : <span class="bengali">উৎপদ</span> but /atthi/ : <span class="bengali">অত্থি</span>.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Assamese output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/. <li> /y/ and /ẏ/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially and at post-consonantal positions. Otherise, /ẏ/ is used.</ul>',
        'Bengali': '<span class="bengali">ৱ</span> is actually an Assamese letter that the converter uses to represent /va/. Bengali script does not contain /va/ in in its native reportoire. Khanda /ta/ is formed automatically depending on the text. It is used word-finally and at positions where /t/ does not form conjoining conjuncts. /tat/ : <span class="bengali">তৎ</span> & /utpāda/ : <span class="bengali">উৎপদ</span> but /atthi/ : <span class="bengali">অত্থি</span>.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Bengali output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/. <li> /y/ and /ẏ/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially and at post-consonantal positions. Otherise, /ẏ/ is used at intervocalic positions.</ul>',
        'Burmese': 'The following are automatically applied to the output text. <ul> <li> Tall /ā/ is automatically used according to the preceding consonant. /kā/ : <span class="burmese">ကာ</span> but /gā/ : <span class="burmese">ဂါ</span> <li> Kinzi is formed automatically. /saṅghaḥ/ : <span class="burmese">သင်္ဃး</span> <li> Repha is similarly formed automatically. /dharma/ : <span class="burmese">ဓရ်္မ</span><li>/ssa/ and /ñña/ are rendered as <span class="burmese">ဿ</span> and <span class="burmese">ည</span> respectively</ul>',
        'Chakma': 'Modern Chakma uses only few restricted conjunct sequences and others are rendered using a visible Virama. However, you can enable an option to use all possible conjuncts.  In accordance with Chakma orthography, the explicit Virama (Maayaa) is used to geminate consonants e.g. <span class="chakma">𑄇𑄨𑄖𑄴𑄳𑄠𑄬 </span>: kittẏe.  <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Chakma output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /y/ and /ẏ/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially. Otherise, /ẏ/ is used at intervocalic and post-consonantal positions.',
        'Devanagari': '<b>Prishtamatra Orthography</b><br/><br/> In this type of orthography, /e/ vowel sign is written before a consonant. For instance, <span class="devanagari">कॎ कॎा कॎे कॎाे</span> instead of  <span class="devanagari">के को कै कौ</span>.<br/><br/> <b> Vowel ॲ </b> <br/><br> This letter is used instead of ऍ in the Marathi language and some Hindi orthographies. You can enable an option to output this letter instead of the usual ऍ.  <br/><br/> <b> Schwa Deletion </b> <br/><br/> In Hindi, Schwa is not explicitly deleted and must be done by the reader based on context. Aksharamukha uses some heuristics and renders the Schwa deleted text, if the associated option is enabled. The rules are described below: <br/> <ul><li>Schwa is removed from the final syllable. महायान : mahāyān. <ul><li> However, it is retained for monosyllabic words. न : na. </ul><li> Schwa is removed from the second syllable in a Trisyllabic words that ends with a vowel other than ‘a’. सबसे : sabse. <ul><li> But it is retained if the final syllable is a conjunct. वसन्ती : vasantī.</ul> <ul><li> It is also retained if the final syllable already has its Schwa deleted. निकल : nikal.</ul> <li>For tetrasyllabic words, Schwa is removed from the second syllable, e.g बातचीत – bātcīt <ul><li> The penultimate Schwa is removed if the final syllable ends with a vowel other than /a/ e.g गुज़रने : guzarne</ul> <ul><li> Schwa is retained if the second syllable is a conjunct. संप्रदाय : sampradāy </ul> <li> Schwa is not deleted in words that have more than four syllables. These tend to be compound words and would need lexical lookup to perform the correct deletion.</ul> A sample Hindi passage with Schwa deletion enabled is shown below.  <br/><br/> बौद्ध धर्म भारत की श्रमण परम्परा से निकला धर्म और दर्शन है । इसके प्रस्थापक महात्मा बुद्ध शाक्यमुनि (गौतम बुद्ध) थे । वे छठवीं से पाँचवीं शताब्दी ईसा पूर्व तक जीवित थे । उनके गुज़रने के अगले पाँच शताब्दियों में, बौद्ध धर्म पूरे भारतीय उपमहाद्वीप में फ़ैला, और अगले दो हज़ार सालों में मध्य, पूर्वी और दक्षिण-पूर्वी जम्बू महाद्वीप में भी फ़ैल गया । आज, बौद्ध धर्म में तीन मुख्य सम्प्रदाय हैं: थेरवाद, महायान और वज्रयान । बौद्ध धर्म को पैंतीस करोड़ से अधिक लोग मानते हैं और यह दुनिया का चौथा सबसे बड़ा धर्म है । <br/><br/>“बुद्ध” वे कहलाते हैं, जिन्होने सालों के ध्यान के बाद यथार्थता का सत्य भाव पहचाना हो । इस पहचान को बोधि नाम दिया गया है । जो भी “अज्ञानता की नींद” से जागते हैं, वे “बुद्ध” कहलाते हैं । कहा जाता है कि बुद्ध शाक्यमुनि केवल एक बुद्ध हैं – उनके पहले बहुत सारे थे और भविष्य में और होंगे । उनका कहना था कि कोई भी बुद्ध बन सकता है अगर वह उनके “धर्म” के अनुसार एक धार्मिक जीवन जीए और अपनी बुद्धि को शुद्ध करे । बौद्ध धर्म का अन्तिम लक्ष्य है इस दुःख भरी स्थिति का अंत । “मैं केवल एक ही पदार्थ सिखाता हूँ – दुःख और दुःख निरोध” (बुद्ध) । बौद्ध धर्म के अनुयायी आर्य अष्टांग मार्ग के अनुसार जीकर अज्ञानता और दुःख से मुक्ति और निर्वाण पाने की कोशिश करते हैं । <br/><br/>bauddh dharm bhārat kī śramaṇ paramparā se niklā dharm aur darśan hai . iske prasthāpak mahātmā buddh śākyamuni (gautam buddh) the . ve chaṭhvīṃ se pām̐cvīṃ śatābdī īsā pūrv tak jīvit the . unke guzarne ke agle pām̐c śatābdiyoṃ meṃ, bauddh dharm pūre bhārtīy upamahādvīp meṃ failā, aur agle do hazār sāloṃ meṃ madhy, pūrvī aur dakṣiṇ-pūrvī jambū mahādvīp meṃ bhī fail gayā . āj, bauddh dharm meṃ tīn mukhy sampradāy haiṃ: thervād, mahāyān aur vajrayān . bauddh dharm ko paiṃtīs karor̤ se adhik log mānte haiṃ aur yah duniyā kā cauthā sabse bar̤ā dharm hai . <br/><br/>“buddh” ve kahlāte haiṃ, jinhone sāloṃ ke dhyān ke bād yathārthatā kā saty bhāv pahcānā ho . is pahcān ko bodhi nām diyā gayā hai . jo bhī “ajñāntā kī nīṃd” se jāgte haiṃ, ve “buddh” kahlāte haiṃ . kahā jātā hai ki buddh śākyamuni keval ek buddh haiṃ – unke pahle bahut sāre the aur bhaviṣy meṃ aur hoṃge . unkā kahnā thā ki koī bhī buddh ban saktā hai agar vah unke “dharm” ke anusār ek dhārmik jīvan jīe aur apnī buddhi ko śuddh kare . bauddh dharm kā antim lakṣya hai is duḥkh bharī sthiti kā aṃt . “maiṃ keval ek hī padārth sikhātā hūm̐ – duḥkh aur duḥkh nirodh” (buddh) . bauddh dharm ke anuyāyī āry aṣṭāṃg mārg ke anusār jīkar ajñāntā aur duḥkh se mukti aur nirvāṇ pāne kī kośiś karte haiṃ .',
        'Grantha': 'The Grantha Nukta is a very modern addition to the Grantha script. It has been used to extend the native reportoire. Noto Sans Grantha has a few bugs but by and large the text should be properly rendered. <br/><br/> You can also toggle between the old-style /au/ sign <span class="grantha">𑌕𑍌</span> and the new-style one <span class="grantha">𑌕𑍗</span>. <br/><br/><b> Prakrit Orthography </b> <br/> When writing Prakrit, Grantha uses the Anusvara as a geminate marker and uses an alternate anusvara above to mark nasalization. <span class="grantha">𑌬𑍁𑌂𑌧𑌀 𑌸𑌰𑌣𑌀 𑌗𑌂𑌛𑌾𑌮𑌿</span> as opposed to <span class="grantha">𑌬𑍁𑌦𑍍𑌧𑌂 𑌸𑌰𑌣𑌂 𑌗𑌚𑍍𑌛𑌾𑌮𑌿</span><br/><br/><b>Old-Style Final forms</b><br/>Pre-modern Grantha sometimes used final forms for other consonants similar to <span class="grantha">𑌤𑍍</span> /t/, <span class="grantha">𑌨𑍍</span> /n/ & <span class="grantha">𑌮𑍍</span> /m/ regularly used in Modern Grantha. <br/><br/><i>New Style:</i> <span class="grantha">𑌅𑌕𑍍 𑌅𑌗𑍍 𑌅𑌙𑍍 𑌅𑌚𑍍 𑌅𑌜𑍍 𑌅𑌞𑍍 𑌅𑌟𑍍 𑌆𑌡𑍍 𑌅𑌣𑍍 𑌅𑌤𑍍 𑌅𑌦𑍍 𑌅𑌨𑍍 𑌅𑌪𑍍 𑌅𑌬𑍍 𑌅𑌮𑍍 𑌅𑌯𑍍 𑌅𑌰𑍍 𑌅𑌲𑍍 𑌅𑌵𑍍 𑌅𑌶𑍍 𑌅𑌷𑍍 𑌅𑌸𑍍 𑌅𑌹𑍍</span><br/><i>Old Style:</i> <span class="granthalig">𑌅𑌕𑍍 𑌅𑌗𑍍 𑌅𑌙𑍍 𑌅𑌚𑍍 𑌅𑌜𑍍 𑌅𑌞𑍍 𑌅𑌟𑍍 𑌆𑌡𑍍 𑌅𑌣𑍍 𑌅𑌤𑍍 𑌅𑌦𑍍 𑌅𑌨𑍍 𑌅𑌪𑍍 𑌅𑌬𑍍 𑌅𑌮𑍍 𑌅𑌯𑍍 𑌅𑌰𑍍 𑌅𑌲𑍍 𑌅𑌵𑍍 𑌅𑌶𑍍 𑌅𑌷𑍍 𑌅𑌸𑍍 𑌅𑌹𑍍</span><br/><br/>There is an option to manually enable this.',
        'GranthaPandya': 'Aksharamukha uses a hack-encoded font that uses Malayalam characters to represent the Pandya Grantha characters. Medieval Grantha does not have its own Unicode block yet. As a result, the font has minor issues. For instance, the Repha will not be rendered properly in Chrome (or any other systems using HarfBuzz). You may want to use Uniscribe supporting programs like MS Word to properly render the text.',
        'Gujarati': 'Avestan <span class="avestan">𐬲</span> is rendered as <span class="gujarati">ૹ</span>. You can also enable an option to remove shwas that appear word finally. /bhautika/ ભૌતિક  : /bhautik/',
        'Javanese': 'Aksharamukha places the repha automatically on the preceding consonants. /karma/ : <span class="javanese">ꦏꦂꦩ</span>.',
        'Kannada': 'As the only South-Indic script to have a native Nukta, it has been utilized to extend the script and create new characters. <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Kannada output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants are replaced by Anusvara when followed by their plosive counterparts. ಗಙ್ಗಾ → ಗಂಗಾ <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. ಗಮ್ → ಗಂ',
        'Kharoshthi': 'The vowel-length indicator is a pretty late feature. Kharoshthi in its earlier stages did not have it. The Segoe UI Historic font in Windows 10 supports a greater range of ligatures than <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansKharoshthi/NotoSansKharoshthi-Regular.otf">Noto Sans Kharoshthi</a>. If you do not see various Kharoshthi ligatures, it is possibly because of the lack of Segoe Historic UI in your system and Noto Sans Kharoshthi is being used as the replacement web font. ',
        'Khudawadi': 'The Nukta has been used to extend the alphabet to represent /ṣ/, South-Indic consonants and the North-Indic Perso-Arabic consonants.',
        'Lepcha': 'There is no Virama and only few consonants have a final vowelless form. Hence, consonants without a final form are approximated to those with final forms. /buddha/ is approximated to /butdha/ <span class="lepcha">ᰓᰪᰳᰌ</span> since final /t/ exists.',
        'Mahajani': 'Mahajani is sort of alphabetic and vowels can have multiple readings. Refer to Script Source and the Unicode proposal for more information.',
        'Modi': 'Modi usually does not distinguish between long and short /u/ and /i/. /u/ and /ū/ are both represented by /u/ and, similarly, /i/ and /ī/ by /ī/. It also approximates the vocalic vowels /ṛ/, /ṝ/, /ḷ/ and /ḹ/ to /rī/ & /lī/. Aksharamukha by default applies this convention to the converted output. To disable this, please select \'preserve source\'',
        'Multani': 'Multani is more-or-less an Abjad with vowels being only explicitly shown in monosyllabic words and at word-initial positions. Otherwise, vowels are not represented. Aksharamukha applies this by default. If you would like to show vowels at all positions, please enable \'preserve source\'.',
        'Khmer': 'Khmer Repha is formed by default. /dharma/ :: <span class="khmer">ធម៌ </span>',
        'Saurashtra': 'The aspirated versions of /n/, /m/, /l/ and /r/ are automatically formed using the \'Haaru\'. nha mha lha rha :: <span class="saurashtra">ꢥꢴ ꢪꢴ ꢭꢴ ꢬꢴ</span>. This can be disabled by enabling <i> Preserve source </i>. <br/><br/><span class="saurashtra">/ꢒ꣄‍ꢰ/</span> conjuncts is automatically formed for /kṣa/.  <br/><br/><b> Avagraha </b> <br/> Since Saurashtra does not have a native Avagraha, the Telugu Avagraha has been borrowed as it fits harmoniously in terms of shape into the script. <br/><br/><b> Saurashtra Haaru in Tamil </b><br/> When writing Saurashtra in Tamil, the sign Haaru that indicates aspiration of /n/, /m/, /l/ and /r/ is written as a colon. Thus, <span class="saurashtra">ꢥꢴꢷ</span> is usually rendered as <span class="tamil">/நீ:/</span>. Aksharamukha does not do this by default and it is usually rendered as <span class="Tamil">/ந்ஹீ/</span>. If one requires the colon to denote aspiration, this can be enabled manually as an extra option - <i>Convert Saurashtra Haaru as :</i>',
        'Siddham': 'Siddham uses several alternate forms for the vowels /i/, /ī/ and /u/ and vowel sign /u/ and /ū. /i/ has two variants <span class="siddham">𑗘</span> and <span class="siddham">𑗙</span>, /ī/ has a variant form <span class="siddham">𑗚</span> and /u/ has a variant form<span class="siddham">𑗛</span>. Vowel signs /u/ and /ū/ have a variant each, <span class="siddham">𑗜 </span> and <span class="siddham">𑗝</span>. These variants can be enabled by choosing the appropriate option in the converter. <br/><br/> There are also several Devanagari-encoded Siddham fonts (see <a href="https://github.com/MihailJP/Muktamsiddham">here</a> and <a href="http://siddham.shikisokuzekuu.net/">here</a>), which can be enabled if required.',
        'Sharada': 'The Nukta has been used to extended to alphabet to represent Perso-Arabic and South-Indic characters. The Sharada extra short vowel mark has been used to create short vowels that do not traditionally exist in Sharada. /æ/ and /ô/ have been denoted using the vowel modifier mark.',
        'SylotiNagri': 'There doesn\'t seem to be a proper agreed way to create Syloti Nagri conjuncts. As a result, Noto Sans SylotiNagri does not form any proper conjuncts. See <a href="https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-fonts/issues/998">here</a>.',
        'TaiTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /ṅ/ in the preceeding consonant. saṅgho → <span class="taitham">ᩈᩘᨥᩮᩣ</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavā → <span class="taitham">ᨽᨣᩅᩤ</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="taitham">ᩔ </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -ā automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -ā can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.',
        'LaoTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /ṅ/ in the preceeding consonant. saṅgho → <span class="laotham">ᩈᩘᨥᩮᩣ</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavā → <span class="laotham">ᨽᨣᩅᩤ</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="laotham">ᩔ </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -ā automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -ā can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.',
        'LueTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /ṅ/ in the preceeding consonant. saṅgho → <span class="luetham">ᩈᩘᨥᩮᩣ</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavā → <span class="luetham">ᨽᨣᩅᩤ</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="luetham">ᩔ </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -ā automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -ā can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.',
        'KhuenTham': 'Aksharamukha does the following automatically<br/><ul><li> Mai Kang Lai is automatically substituted for consonantal /ṅ/ in the preceeding consonant. saṅgho → <span class="khuentham">ᩈᩘᨥᩮᩣ</span><li>Tall /a/ is used for /va/, /da/, /dha/ & /ga/. bhagavā → <span class="khuentham">ᨽᨣᩅᩤ</a> <li> /ssa/ is rendered with <span class="khuentham">ᩔ </span></ul>. <br/>Some fonts create the tall form of -ā automatically without it being explictly chosen. The explicit choice of Tall -ā can be disabled to allow such fonts to choose the appropriate form implicitly.',
        'Tamil': '<b> Superscripted Tamil </b> <br/>Tamil has a deficient script compared to other Indic scripts as it lacks distinct characters for many voiced and aspirated consonants. Publishers ha/d to resort to the use of superscript (and sometimes subscript) numerals to represent these letters in Tamil. <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Tamil output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li>Anusvara and Chandrabindu are replaced by the corresponding nasal consonant if followed by a plosive. <span class="tamil">சம்ʼத³</span> → <span class="tamil">சந்த³</span> <li>Intervocalic /ந/ is replaced by /ன/. <span class="tamil">மநஸா</span> → <span class="tamil">மனஸா</span></ul><!--<b> Medieval e/o with Pulli </b><br/><br/> As a Brahmi-derived script, Tamil did not have atomic glyphs for short /e/ and short /o/ (as Brahmi was originally devised for Prakrit, which lacked them phonemically). Therefore, the Tamil Virama \'Pulli\' was used a vowel-length reducer. This was the case for around two millenia it was changed sometime around the 1700\'s. You can enable this option and choose to display this orthography. <br/><br/> ĕ ŏ ke kŏ : எ ஒ கே கொ (Medieval) : எ் ஒ் கெ் கெ்ா (Modern)<br/><br>--> <b>Old Orthography</b><br/>The Tamil script was reformed in 1978 to normalize the script and remove some ligatured syllables. The following ligatured syllables were reformed to their respective non-ligatured forms. <br/><br/> <i>Old orthography:</i> <span class="tamilold">னை ணை லை ளை னா ணா றா</span><br/> <i>New orthography:</i> <span class="tamil">னை ணை லை ளை னா ணா றா</span> (New) <br/><br/> This can be enabled as an option. <a href="https://www.fontsc.com/font/lohit-tamil-classical">Lohit Tamil Classical</a> supports the old orthography. <br/><br/> <b>Contextual ள</b><br/>Tamil (and South Indian Sanskrit fort tha matter) sometimes uses the retroflex /l/ ள for classical Sanskrits words. For instance, <span class="tamil">ப்ரவாள</span> /pravāl̤a/, <span class="tamil">ப்ரளய</span> /pral̤aya/, <span class="tamil">நாமாவளி</span> /nāmāval̤i/ for classical sanskrit words <i>pravāla</i>, <i>pralaya</i> and <i>nāmāvali</i>. This can be enabled in the converter. Few simples rules of thumbs are used to predict the appearance of the retroflex l. However, as of now this is an experimental feature.<br/><br/><b> Tamil Transcription </b><br/>Tamil has a very phonemic orthography and as such the orthographic does not accurately represent the pronunciation of the text. Consonants have multiple values based on their positionn in the word based on following simple rules of the thumb. Note that it might not work for non-native words, which tend to retain their original prounciation. <br/> <ul><li> Intervocalic /k/, /ṭ/, /t/ and /p/ and post-nasal plosives /k/, /c/, /ṭ/, /t/ and /p/ are replaced by their voiced counterparts. e.g. நகம் /nakam/ : /nagam/ <li> Word-initial and intervolic /c/ is replaced by /s/. சந்தை /cantai/ : /sandai/ <li> ற்ற் /ṟṟ/ and ன்ற் /ṉṟ/ are replaced by /ṭr/ and /ṇḍr/<br/><br/></ul> Sample Text: <br/><br/> <span class="tamil">கெடில ஆற்றின் வடகரையில் விளங்கும் திருவதிகை என்னும் வீரட்டானத் திருப்பதியில் உகந்தெழுந்தருளியிருக்கும் தலைவனே! யான் இப்பிறப்பில் என் அறிவு அறியப் பல கொடுஞ் செயல்களைச் செய்தேனாக எனக்குத் தோன்றவில்லை. அவ்வாறாகச் சூலைநோய், யாருக்கும் நோய்முதல் புலப்படாத வகையில் என் வயிற்றினுள் குடலோடு ஏனைய உள் உறுப்புக்களைக் கட்டிச் செயற்படாமல் மடக்குதலால் அடியேன் அவ்வலியைப் பொறுக்க இயலாதேனாக உள்ளேன். கூற்றுவனைப் போல அந்நோய் அடியேனைத் துன்புறுத்தும் செயலை நீக்கும் ஆற்றலுடையீர். அந்நோயை விலக்கினால் எப்பொழுதும் காளை மீது ஊரும் உம் அடிக்கண் நீங்காமல் மனத்தால் துணிவும் தலையால் தணிவும் மொழியால் பணிவும் தோன்ற வணங்குவேன்.</span> <br/><br/>keḍila āṭrin vaḍagaraiyil viḷaṅgum tiruvadigai ennum vīraṭṭānat tiruppadiyil ugandeḻundaruḷiyirukkum talaivanē! yān ippiṟappil en aṟivu aṟiyap pala koḍuñ jeyalgaḷaic ceydēnāga enakkut tōṇḍravillai. avvāṟāgac cūlainōy, yārukkum nōymudal pulappaḍāda vagaiyil en vayiṭrinuḷ kuḍalōḍu ēnaiya uḷ uṟuppukkaḷaik kaṭṭic ceyaṟpaḍāmal maḍakkudalāl aḍiyēn avvaliyaip poṟukka iyalādēnāga uḷḷēn. kūṭruvanaip pōla annōy aḍiyēnait tunbuṟuttum seyalai nīkkum āṭraluḍaiyīr. annōyai vilakkināl eppoḻudum kāḷai mīdu ūrum um aḍikkaṇ nīṅgāmal manattāl tuṇivum talaiyāl taṇivum moḻiyāl paṇivum tōṇḍra vaṇaṅguvēn.',
        'TamilBrahmi': 'To get finer orthogrgraphic variations try <a href="https://tamiljinavani.appspot.com">Jinavani</a>',
        'Sinhala': '<b> Sanskrit/Pali Orthography in Sinhala </b> <br/><br/> When Sinhala is used to write Sanskrit/Pali text, sometimes the short e/o are used to represent the Sanskrit long e/o. For instance, <span class="sinhala">නමො භගවතෙ</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">නමෝ භගවතේ</span> <br/><br/><b> Conjuncts </b> <br/><br/> Modern Sinhala does not extensively use conjuncts except for /kṣa/ and the post-base forms of /ya/ (as in /kya/: <span class="sinhala">ක්‍ය</span>) and /ra/ (as in /kra/: <span class="sinhala">ක්‍ර</span>). Aksharamukha forms these automatically. However, older texts, particularly for Pali/Sanskrit, extensively used conjuncts and Repha. For instance, <span class="sinhala">සම‍්මාසම‍්බුද්‍ධස‍්ස</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">සම්මාසම්බුද්ධස්ස</span>. Notice the use of conjoining conjuncts such as <span class="sinhala">ද්‍ධ</span> and touching letters such as <span class="sinhala">ස‍්ස</span>. Also, <span class="sinhala">ධර්‍ම</span> instead of <span class="sinhala">ධර්ම</span>. This can be enabled by selecting \'enable all conjuncts\' as an option. <br/><br/> With the both of the above options enabled, the above example Pali verse will be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="sinhala">යෙ ධම‍්මා හෙතුප‍්පභවා තෙසං හෙතුං තථාගතො ආහ . <br/> තෙසඤ්‍ච යො නිරොධො එවං වාදී මහාසමණො ..</span> <br/><br> And the Sanskrit text as: <br/><br/> <span class="sinhala">අනිරොධම් අනුත‍්පාදම් අනුච‍්ඡෙදම් අශාශ‍්වතම් . <br/> අනෙකාර්‍ථම් අනානාර්‍ථම් අනාගමම් අනිර්‍ගමම් .. <br/> යඃ ප්‍රතීත්‍යසමුත‍්පාදං ප්‍රපඤ්‍චොපශමං ශිවම් . <br/> දෙශයාමාස සංබුද්‍ධස‍්තං වන්‍දෙ වදතාං වරම් ..</span>',
        'TamilExtended': 'An attempt in a printed publication to employ this system is shown below as used in the text called <a href="http://www.archive.org/stream/bhojacharitrama00sastgoog">Bhojacharitram</a>, published in 1916. <br/><img src="../statics/Grantha_Pulli.jpg"><br/> <span class="tamilextended">പ്രാര്ധ്യന്തസ്യ നാശഞ് ച <br/>മുഞ്ജഃ സമ്ക്ഷീയതാമിതി ॥ <br/> വിഘ്നേശഞ് സ മഹേശഞ് ച । <br/> ഹരിമ് നഗരവാസിനഃ <br/> നദീപര്വത മാസേദുഃ <br/>വിപ്രാ ദേശാന്തരമ് യയുഃ ॥</span> <br/> <br/>prārdhyantasya nāśañ ca <br/>muñjaḥ samkṣīyatāmiti .. <br/>vighneśañ sa maheśañ ca . <br/>harim nagaravāsinaḥ <br/>nadīparvata māseduḥ <br/>viprā deśāntaram yayuḥ ..<br/><br/> A <a href="https://groups.google.com/d/msg/mintamil/tDwV_UwYJKc/AVCkX2KQFV4J">commentary</a> on the Jaina Epic Nilakesi published in 1936 also uses this technique intermittently to disambiguate Sanskrit words that will otherwise be ambigous in the Tamil script, along with the proper Grantha script for Sanskrit quotations. There also been other recent publications that employed this method to print Sanskrit.<br/><br/><b>Ligated u & ū</b><br/> Normally, when Grantha consonants are subsumed under Tamil orthography, they do not use ligating signs to represent the vowels u & ū in consonants. However, this results increasing the horizontal space and insufficient visual harmony with the Tamil script, whose consonants usually take a ligating form for the vowels. Therefore, we have innovated Tamil-style ligation for Grantha consonants, hoping that they will be blending in harmoniously with the Tamil script <br/><br/> <i> Non-Ligated </i> <span class="tamilextended"><br>ഖു ഖൂ ഗു ഗൂ ഘു ഘൂ<br/>ഛു ഛൂ ഝു ഝൂ<br/>ഠു ഠൂ ഡു ഡൂ ഢു ഢൂ<br/>ഥു ഥൂ ദു ദൂ ധു ധൂ<br/>ഫു ഫൂ ബു ബൂ ഭു ഭൂ</span>. <br/><br/><i> Ligated Style </i> <br/><span class="tamilextended"> ഖ‍ു ഖ‍ൂ ഗ‍ു ഗ‍ൂ ഘ‍ു ഘ‍ൂ<br/>ഛ‍ു ഛ‍ൂ ഝ‍ു ഝ‍ൂ<br/>ഠ‍ു ഠ‍ൂ ഡ‍ു ഡ‍ൂ ഢ‍ു ഢ‍ൂ<br/>ഥ‍ു ഥ‍ൂ ദ‍ു ദ‍ൂ ധ‍ു ധ‍ൂ<br/>ഫ‍ു ഫ‍ൂ ബ‍ു ബ‍ൂ ഭ‍ു ഭ‍ൂ</span><br/><br/>The spacing signs are in wide-spread use for the Tamilized Grantha consonants <span class="tamilextended">ജ ശ ഷ സ ഹ ക്ഷ ശ്‍ര</span>. However, in order to be symmetric, ligated forms have been innovated for them as well.<br/><br/><i> Non-Ligated </i> <span class="tamilextended"><br>ജു ജൂ <br/>ശു ശൂ സു സൂ ഷു ഷൂ ഹു ഹൂ <br/>ശ്‍രു ശ്‍രൂ ക്ഷു ക്ഷൂ</span><br/><br/><i> Ligated Style </i> <br/><span class="tamilextended"> ജ‍ു ജ‍ൂ <br/>ശ‍ു ശ‍ൂ സ‍ു സ‍ൂ ഷ‍ു ഷ‍ൂ ഹ‍ു ഹ‍ൂ <br/>ശ്‍ര‍ു ശ്‍ര‍ൂ ക്ഷ‍ു ക്ഷ‍ൂ</span><br/><br/>Users can choose the appropriate ligation style from the options. <br/><br/><b>Serif Font </b></br> There is also a  serif style font called <a href="">Agastya Serif</a>. Using this Serif style, the above verse will appear as: <br/><br/><span class="tamilextendedserif">പ്രാര്ധ്യന്തസ്യ നാശഞ് ച <br/>മുഞ്ജഃ സമ്ക്ഷീയതാമിതി ॥ <br/> വിഘ്നേശഞ് സ മഹേശഞ് ച । <br/> ഹരിമ് നഗരവാസിനഃ <br/> നദീപര്വത മാസേദുഃ <br/>വിപ്രാ ദേശാന്തരമ് യയുഃ ॥</span>',
        'Thaana': 'Aksharamukha automatically uses އް to denote gemination. When އް appears as a glottal stop (at the end of words), it is denoted using ʔ. The Arabic-specific characters in Thaana are approximated to their closest Indic counterparts. <br/><br/><b>Archaic /ṇ/ </b><br/><br/> The archaic /ṇ/ ޱ is only used when the <i>Preserve source</i> option is enabled, else it is replaced by /n/ ނ by default.',
        'MeeteiMayek': 'Aksharamukha uses final consonants where available and resorts to using the explicit Virama for others. <br/><br/><b> Archaic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Historically, Meetei Mayek had characters for the following: ī ū aḥ cha ña ṭa ṭha ḍa ḍha ṇa śa ṣa :: <span class="meeteimayek">ꯑꫫ ꯑꫬ ꯑꫵ ꫢ ꫣ ꫤ ꫥ ꫦ ꫧ ꫨ ꫩ ꫪ ꫪ</span>. But, they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: i u ah ca na ta tha da dha na sa sa :: <span class="meeteimayek">ꯏ ꯎ ꯑꯍ꯭ ꯆ ꯅ ꯇ ꯊ ꯗ ꯙ ꯅ ꯁ ꯁ</span>. The historic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled.',
        'Malayalam': 'Chillus are formed automatically based on context in the output text.  /dharma/ becomes <span class="malayalam">ധർമ</span> according to Malayalam orthographic conventions and not <span class="malayalam">ധര്മ</span><br/><br/>By default, Chillus in the input Malayalam text are not explicitly marked in the output script. To show Chillus in the converted text, enable <i>Show Chillus</i> in the input section. Chillus will then be shown followed by a ˍ in the target script. <span class="malayalam">/ധർമ/</span> : dharˍma <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Malayalam output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants and Anusvara are placed contextually. veṃkaṭa : <span class="malayalam">വേങ്കട</span> but gaṅgā : <span class="malayalam">ഗംഗാ</span> <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. </ul> <br/> <b> Traditional Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Switches to a web font that supports Traditional orthography. <span class="malayalamold">വസ്തു</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">വസ്തു</span>. The font (Meera) used for the traditional orthography can be downloaded from <a href="https://github.com/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/blob/master/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/Meera-Regular.ttf">here</a>. <br/><br/> <b> Prakrit Orthography </b> <br/><br/> When writing Prakrit, Malayalam uses the Anusvara as a geminate marker and uses an alternate anusvara above to mark nasalization. <span class="malayalamold">ബുംധഀ സരണഀ ഗംഛാമി </span> as opposed to <span class="malayalam">ബുദ്ധം സരണം ഗച്ഛാമി</span> <br/><br/> <b> Archaic II and AU </b> <br/><br/> Old Malayalam used <span class="malayalam">ൟ കൌ</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">ഈ കൗ</span> <br/><br/> <b> Dot Reph </b> <br/><br/> Pre-script reform Malayalam used a Repha instead of the /ra/ Chillu before consonants. <span class="malayalam">ധൎമായ</span> instead of <span class="malayalam">ധർമായ</span>',
        'PhagsPa': 'PhagsPa does not use conjuncts except for subjoined -r,-v- and -y. Instead, it splits the words in syllabic chunks of the forms - [C]V, [C]VC and CCV. Thus <i>samudgate</i> becomes <i>sa mud ga te</i> <span class="phagspa">ꡛ ꡏꡟꡊ ꡂ ꡈꡠ</span>and <i>kleśa</i> becomes <i>kle śa</i> <span class="phagspa">ꡀꡙꡠ ꡚ</span>. However, this leads to an ambiguity. A word like <span class="phagspa">ꡛꡈ ꡋ</span> can be read as <i>stana</i> or <i>satna</i> in the absense of the any vowel signs. <br/><br/> Aksharamukha converts the input text into syllabic chunks automatically and also reverses thep process for the transliteration from PhagsPa to other scripts. ᠂ U+1802 is used as the word separator in PhagsPa text.  <br/><br/> There are two styles of PhagsPa Script, Tibetan-styel and Seal Scrit-style as show below. These can be switched through options. The fonts for these versions can be downloaded from <a href="https://www.babelstone.co.uk/Fonts/Phags-pa.html">here</a>. <br/><br/> <b> Tibetan Style </b> <div class="phagspatib">ꡳꡡ ᠂ ꡋ ꡏꡡ ᠂ ꡎꡟꡊ ꡊꡜꡖ ꡗ</div> <br/><br/> <b> Seal Script Style <div class="phagspaseal">ꡳꡡ ᠂ ꡋ ꡏꡡ ᠂ ꡎꡟꡊ ꡊꡜꡖ ꡗ</div> <br/><br/></b> Windows 10 uses Microsoft PhagsPa to display the PhagsPa text. In the absence of this font, <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansPhagsPa/NotoSansPhagsPa-Regular.otf">Noto Sans PhagsPa</a> is used to display the text.',
        'IPA': 'The IPA conversion is based on the normalized prescriptive pronunication expected from a Sanskrit text. This may not accurately reflect variations that usually occur based on the target script or even based on the region it is being read. It will for most part fail for scripts like Malayalam and Bengali as they have a phonemic orthography. <br/><br/> <b> Tamil </b> <br/><br/> For Tamil to IPA conversion, the results are mirrored from <a href="http://anunaadam.appspot.com">Anunaadam</a> which is far more accurate. <br/><br/> <b> Oriya </b> <br/><br/> The transcription follows the ruled provided <a href="https://github.com/OdiaWikimedia/Converter/blob/master/IPA-Romanization/ipa-roman">here</a> as Oriyan phonetics is a bit different to that of the other Indian languages such as the inherent vowel being /ɔ/ instead of /ə/.',
        'Telugu': ' <b> New Telugu characters </b> <br/><span class="telugu">ఴ</span> is a historic Telugu letter that is equivalent to Tamil ழ. And Telugu also has it own Candrabindu character <span class="telugu">అఀ</span>. Being new characters, your Telugu font may not adequately support these characters. Please use an updated font to view these characters. <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/>The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Telugu output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Pure nasal consonants are replaced by Anusvara when followed by their plosive counterparts. <span class="telugu">గఙ్గా → గంగా</span> <li>  Word-final consonantal /m/ is replaced by Anusvara. <span class="telugu">గమ్ → గం</span></ul><b>Telugu Repha (Valapala Gilaka)</b><br/>In Pre-Modern Telugu, it was common to use a reph-sign (called <i>Valapala Gilaka</i>) for pre-consonantal /r/. For instance, <span class="telugu">ధర్‍మ</span> (c.f Modern Kannada <span class="kannada">ಧರ್ಮ</span>) as opposed to the modern <span class="telugu">ధర్మ</span>. This can be manualy enabled if required. However, this only works with Noto Sans Telugu.<br/><br/><b>Telugu phonemes æ & ǣ</b><br/>The phonemes /æ/ and /ǣ/ do exist in Telugu phonology but do not have orthographically distinct forms. For instance, the syllable /æ/ is usually represented as <span class="telugu">కె​</span> /kĕ/ or <span class="telugu">క్యా</span> /kyā/. However, Telugu linguists tend to use an underine beneath /ĕ/ and /e/ to unambiguously represent /æ/ and /ǣ/ as in <span class="telugu">ఎ॒​ కె॒</span> & <span class="telugu">ఏ॒​ కే॒​</span>. You can see more about this in <a href="http://www.unicode.org/L2/L2020/20120-telugu-underline.pdf">L2/20-120</a>. Extrapolating this, the phoneme /ô/ is represented as /o/ with underline <span class="telugu">ఒ॒​ కొ॒​</span>.<br/><br/><b>Tamil-Style letters</b><br/>When transcribing Tamil, sometimes, specifically in SriVaishnava literature, it is common to see Tamil-style glyphs for /<span class="telugu">ఴ</span>/ and /<span class="telugu">ఱ</span>/. You can read in detail about this specific orthographic practice in <a href="http://www.unicode.org/L2/L2020/20119-two-telugu-letters.pdf">L2/20-119</a>. For instance, the following Tamil verse could be transcribed as follows: <br/><br/><span class="tamil">வையத்து வாழ்வீர்காள்! நாமும் நம் பாவைக்குச் <br/>செய்யும் கிரிசைகள் கேளீரோ, பாற்கடலுள் <br/>பையத் துயின்ற பரமனடி பாடி <br/>நெய்யுண்ணோம் பாலுண்ணோம் நாட்காலே நீராடி <br/>மையிட்டு எழுதோம் மலரிட்டு நாம் முடியோம் <br/>செய்யாதன செய்யோம் தீக்குறளை சென்று ஓதோம் <br/>ஐயமும் பிச்சையும் ஆந்தனையும் கைகாட்டி <br/>உய்யுமாறு எண்ணி உகந்து ஏல் ஓர் எம்பாவாய்</span> <br/><br/> <span class="teluguzha">వైయత్తు వాఴ్వీర్గాళ్! నాముం నం పావైక్కుచ్<br/>చెయ్యుం కిరిసైగళ్ కేళీరో, పాౘ్కడలుళ్<br/>పైయత్ తుయిండ్ర పరమనడి పాడి</br>నెయ్యుణ్ణోం పాలుణ్ణోం నాట్కాలే నీరాడి<br/>మైయిట్టు ఎఴుదోం మలరిట్టు నాం ముడియోం<br/>సెయ్యాదన సెయ్యోం తీక్కుౘళై సెండ్రు ఓదోం<br/>ఐయముం పిచ్చైయుం ఆందనైయుం కైగాట్టి<br/>ఉయ్యుమాౘు ఎణ్ణి ఉగందు ఏల్ ఓర్ ఎంబావాయ్</span><br/><br/>This can be enabled using the appropriate options. Also, it is necessary to enable Tamil transcription in the input section, in case you are transcribing directly from the Tamil script. You also need to use <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/AazhvaarTelugu.otf">Aazvhvaar Telugu</a> font to display the Tamil-style letters properly. Without the font, the letters will appear as <span class="telugu">ఴ</span> & <span class="telugu">ౘ</span>.',
        'Tibetan': 'The Sanskrit phonemes /c/, /ch/, /j/ and /jh/ are mapped to consonants TSA, TSHA, DZA and DZHA, respectively (according to Tibetan conventions). This can be changed by selecting the <i>Use Sanskrit palatals</i> options, which will use the Sanskrit-specific consonants <span class="tibetan">ཅ ཆ ཇ ཇྷ</span> instead of <span class="tibetan">ཙ ཚ ཛ ཛྷ</span> . <br/><br/> Tibetan Mark TSA-PHRU is used as the Nukta. /yya/, /rya/, /rva/ and /vva/ are indicated using the full-subjoined forms as <span class="tibetan">ཡྻ, ཪྻ, ཪྺ, ཝྺ</span>. Also, <span class="tibetan">ཞ</span> is replaced with /jḧa/ and <span class="tibetan">འ</span> with /a/. <span class="tibetan">༈</span> and <span class="tibetan">༈</span> become Dandas. <br/><br/> <b> Dbu-Med Style </b> <br/><br/> You can also enable to choose the Dbu-Med style for displaying Tibetan instead of the usual Dbu-Can style. Aksharamukha uses the Qomolangma-Betsu font from <a href="http://www.yalasoo.com/English/docs/yalasoo_en_font.html">here</a>.  <br/><br/> <span class="tibetan">ཨོཾ་ན་མོ་བུ་དྡྷཱ་ཡ</span> (Dbu-Can) <br/> <span class="tibetandbumed">ཨོཾ་ན་མོ་བུ་དྡྷཱ་ཡ</span> (Dbu-Med) <br/><br/> <b> Nativization Conventions </b> <br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Tibetan output in according with Tibetan orthographic practices. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/ at intervocalic positions and if followed by consonantal /r/ </li> <li>Spaces are replaced by Tshegs ་</li> <li> Explicit Virama is not shown </li><ul>',
        'Brahmi': 'The Segoe UI Historic font in Windows 10 supports a greater range of ligatures than <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/googlei18n/noto-fonts/phaseIII_only/unhinted/otf/NotoSansBrahmi/NotoSansBrahmi-Regular.otf">Noto Sans Brahmi</a>. If you do not see various Brahmi ligatures, it is possibly because of the lack of Segoe Historic UI in your system and Noto Sans Brahmi is being used as the replacement web font.',
        'Kaithi': 'Devanagari numerals have been used as Kaithi seems to lack a numeral set of its own. Devanagari Avagraha has been borrowed for the same reason as well. U+2E31 is used as the word separator. The Nukta has been used to extend the alphabet to represent /ṣ/, South-Indic consonants and the North-Indic Perso-Arabic consonants.',
        'Vatteluttu': 'Vatteluttu is not yet enocoded in Unicode. Aksharamukha uses a hack-encoded font that uses the Tamil block to encode Vatteluttu. It does not contain /j/, /ś/, /ṣ/, /s/ and /h/ (as in Modern Tamil) in its reportoire as Grantha letters were usually augmented with Vatteluttu characters to represent them',
        'Tirhuta': 'The Nukta was used to extend the characters to create equivalents of South-Indic and other Nukta-ted characters that typically occur in North Indic scripts.',
        'Takri': 'Devanagari Avagraha has been used to denote Avagraha in Takri as well. The Nukta was used to extend the characters to create equivalents of South-Indic and other Nukta-ted characters that typically occur in North Indic scripts. <br/><br/><b>Medieval Takri</b><br/>In Medieval Takri, /kha/ can stand for both /ṣa/ and /kha/ depending on the context. This can be enabled by selecting the appropriate option. <br/><br/> <b> Consonant Gemination </b> <br/> In Takri orthography, the gemination of consonants is not usually written. Thus /uttara/ is usually written as <span class="takri"> 𑚄𑚙𑚤 </span> /utara/ and not <span class="takri">𑚄𑚙𑚶𑚙𑚤</span> /uttara/. This can be manually enabled as well.',
        'Urdu': 'Urdu is an abjad. It amounts to short-vowels being not written and /v/ and /y/ also denoting long vowels. (The following assumes the consonants have an inherent /a/ like Indic scripts for illustration.). In the absense of short vowels, /ava/ can stand for /va/, /ū/, /o/ or /au/, /aya/ can stand for /ya/, /ī/, /e/ or /ai/. On the same note /kava/ could be /kava/, /kū/, /ko/, /kau/ and /kaya/ could be /kaya/, /kī/, /ke/ or /kai/, Thus /kayarala/ probably should be read /kerala/ and /hayadarābād/ as /haidarābād/. Additionally, the short-vowels (i/u) have to be guessed by context. As in North-Indic scripts, the Schwa deletion is also not shown explicitly. Ideally, /urdū/ should be written as /اُرْدُو/ but it is often written as /اردو/ (aradava). One should know that the first vowel is a short /u/, the schwa /a/ in r is deleted, and /va/ in this case denotes /ū/. Thus giving the reading <s>a</s><sup>u</sup>r<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>ū</sup>. /میں/ (mayaṃ) must be read m<s>(aya)</s><sup>e</sup>ṃ /meṃ/, /ہندوستان/ (hanadavasatāna) is read h<s>a</s><sup>i</sup>n<s>a</s>d<s>(ava)</s><sup>ū</sup>s<s>a</s>tān<s>a</s> /hindūstān/.<br/><br/> Aksharamukha approximates the Arabic-specific consonants to their nearest Indic counterparts and Hamza is shown with an underscore. Ayin is mapped to /a/. Fathatan becomes just an /n/. <br/><br/> If your Urdu text does not show vowel marks, please select the appropriate option to get the proper output. In this way, Aksharamukha assumes all consonants have an inherent /a/ and the Mater Lectionis i.e. /v/ and /y/ are rendered as consonants. The reader has to guess the appropriate reading based on context (as shown above).',
        'Tagalog': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/. Some Tagalog fonts have a character for /r/ but it is not officially encoded in Unicode.',
        'Tagbanwa': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Buhid': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Hanunoo': 'In Phillippine scripts, /i/ denotes both /i/ and /e/ and /u/ denotes both /u/ and /o/.',
        'Sundanese': '<b> Archaic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Sundanese had characters for the following: ṛ, ḷ and bha :: <span class="sundanese">ᮻ ᮼ ᮽ</span>, but they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: reu, leu and ba :: <span class="sundanese">ᮛᮩ ᮜᮩ ᮘ</span>. The archaic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled. <br/><br/> <b>Archaic Conjuncts</b> <br/><br/> Sundanese also had subjointed version of ma and wa, and also final-consonantal form for /k/ and /m/. For instance, <span class="sundanese">ᮊᮬ /kma/,  ᮊᮭ /kva/, ᮃᮾ /ak/, ᮃᮿ /am/ </span> as opposed to <span class="sundanese"> ᮊ᮪ᮙ, ᮊ᮪ᮝ, ᮃᮊ᮪ and ᮃᮊ᮪.</span>This can be manually enabled in the coverter.<br/><br/>',
        'Limbu': '<b> Mukhphreng and Kemphreng </b><br/><br/> The Glottal Stop (Mukhphreng) is transliterated using ʔ and the Kemphreng (Vowel Lengthening Mark), when ocurring with vowels other than /i/ and /u/ is denoted by ꞉ U+A789.<br/><br/> <b> Historic Orthography </b> <br/><br/> Limbu had characters for the following: jha ña ṣa ṃ :: <span class="limbu">ᤉ ᤊ ᤚ ᤲ</span>, but they are not in vogue any more. By default, Aksharamukha does not use these characters. They are replaced by their closest approximations: ja na śa ṅ :: <span class="limbu">ᤈ ᤏ ᤙ ᤱ</span>. The historic characters are used only if the <i>preserve script</i> option is enabled. <br/><br/> <b>Limbu Devanagari Transliteration Convention</b> <br/><br/> Limbu has its own convention, when transliterating to Devanagari. It uses vowels with Nuktas and Visarga to denote the vowel-lengthening. For instance,  <span class="limbu"> ᤀᤧ ᤀᤨ ᤀᤧ᤺ ᤁᤧ ᤁᤨ ᤁᤧ᤺  </span> is transliterated as: <span class="limbudeva">ए़ ओ़ ए़ः के़ को़ के़ः  </span> instead of ऎ ऒ ऎ꞉ कॆ कॊ कॆ꞉. The above sample text would be rendered as <br/><br/> <span class="limbudeva">आङ्गाॽ पेन्सःन् के़लःम्बाॽ मनाआ॥ आहिम् फुङ्ले़ङ्, आङ्गाॽ आत्तिन्नाङ् साम्‌योनिबा, साम्‌योथिम्हाॽ नसाःन् मे़न्जोक्नाबा आ॥ थिक्‌येम् किप्मा केघुबा तुक्माल्ले याङ्साङ्, सिदाबाङ्दाॽ मे़त्छिङ्से़ पेगाङ्साङ् मे़न्नूबा कर ये़सुमाङ्ओ नसान् चाेःक् हेम्तुङाङ्धो आङ्गा वेत्ताङ् बारो॥ - लाल बहादुर लिम्बु. कङ् नुसियेक्पा याक्पङ्गे़म्बा सेसे चुम्लुङ् कालेम्पोङ् बा चइत्‌रो॥ आल्लबा ये़त्छिॽगेम्पा सेसे चुम्लुङ् ११ अक्तुबर २०१४ सिलिगुदि ५०० मनालम्मो पाेःङ्ल पत्लो॥</span><br/><br/>The converter applies this convention if this option is selected.  <br/><br/> <b>SAI-I for Vowel Legnth</b><br/><br/> Limbu has two orthographic conventions. One that uses the SA-I to denote vowel-lengthening and final-forms for the regular vowel - <span class="limbu">ᤁᤢᤴ /kun/ vs ᤁᤢᤏ᤻ /kūn/</span>. In the latter, the vowel-lengthening is explicitly shown using Kemphreng - <span class="limbu">ᤁᤢᤴ /kun/ vs ᤁᤢ᤺ᤴ /kūn/</span>. Aksharamukha by default uses the latter but you can also select the first orthography.',
        'Lao': 'Lao lacks several consonants required to accurately write Pali and therefore transliteration of Pali/Sanskrit is lossy with several inconsistent approximations. Non-Brahmic lao-specific consonants are sometimes used in transcribing Pali, particularly /ດ/, /ບ/, /ຟ/ and  /ຮ/. The first three are transliterated using the Nukta as /d̈/, /p̈/ and /b̈/, and the last one is mapped to /ṟ/. As noted earlier, the conventions are pretty inconsistent. Sometimes, /ດ/ is used to mark gemination but other times it is indicated by plain duplication of consonants, even within the same text. For instance, <a href="http://www.watmai.com.au/373837713732375437693732374537713737.html">here</a> you find: <br/><br/> ອິຕິປິໂສ  ພະຄະວາ  ອະຣະຫັງສັມມາສັມພຸທໂທ  ວິຊຊາຈະຣະນະສັມປັນໂນ ສຸຄະໂຕ  ໂລກະວິທູ  ອະນຸຕຕະໂຣ  ປຸຣິສະທັມມະສະຣະຖີ  ສັຕຖາເທວະມະນຸສສານັງ<br/> itipiso bagavā arahaṅsammāsambuddo vijjācaranasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasarathī satthādevamanussānaṅ <br/><br/> ອິຕິປິໂສ ພະຄະວາ ອະຣະຫັງສັມມາ ສັມພຸດໂທ ວິດຊາຈາຣະນະສັມປັນໂນ ສຸຄະໂຕ ໂລກະວິທູ ອະນຸດ ຕະໂລ ປຸຣິສະທັມມັດສະຣະຖີ ສັດຖາເທວະມະນຸດສານັງ  <br/> itipiso bagavā arahaṅsammā sambud̈do vid̈jācāranasampanno sugato lokavidū anud̈ talo purisadammad̈sarathī sad̈thādevamanud̈sānaṅ  <br/><br/> On a similar note, /r/ and /l/ are sometimes mixed and /ṟ/ may be used for /r/ as in /ຮັກສາ/ (ṟaksā). /p̈b/ is also used to denoted geminated /b/, apart from /bb/ as in /ສັບເພ/ (sap̈be) and /ສັພເພ/ (sabbe). And ຳ is occasionally also used to denote gemination of /m/ as in /ສໍາມາສໍາພຸດໂທ/ (sāṃmāsāṃbud̈do), which can be seen <a href="http://yarkhu.blogspot.com/2017/08/blog-post.html">here</a>. /cha/ is also replaced by /sa/ as in /ຄັດ​ສາ​ມິ/ (gacchāmi) or / ຄັສສະມິ/ (gasami) or even /gacsami/ for /gacchāmi/. ຍ /ñ/ is used for both /ñ/ and /y/ as in /ñakkha/ instead of /yakkha/ (Since /ຍ/ is technically cognate to brahmic /ya/ and only later came to represent /ñ/ phonetically) and /kg/ can also represent /gg/. Refer <a href="http://www.pali.pratyeka.org/#Laoaccent">here</a> for more quirks of Laotian Pali  <br/><br/>Maha Sila Viravong made additiions to the Lao script to express Pali phonology properly and created a one-to-one correspondance with the Brahmic set of consonants. Please refer to Lao (Pali) for further information. <h5> Lao nativation </h5> The following are applied to the output based on the above Laotians conventions <br/><br/> 1. /cha/ is mapped to /sa/ <br/> 2. Both /ya/ and /ña/ are mapped to /ña/ (ຍ) <br/> 2. /d̈/ is used to mark gemination for /d/, /t/, /th/ and /s/ <br/> 3. /p̈/ is used as the gemination marker for /p/ and /b/',
        'LaoPali': 'The Buddhist Institute of Vientiane, using the expanded script, has published several books such as Dhammapada and Pali Grammar. Their aim was to make Pali more accessible to the common public. A few modern publications have been printed using the additiona characters in an attempt to propose an etymological orthography for Lao and make Pali accessible. Please refer to the Unicode <a href="https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2017/17106r-lao-for-pali.pdf">proposal</a> for further information. <br/><br/><b> Lao Orthography </b> <br/>This applies the following conventions: <br/> <ul><li> Replace Anusvara with /ṅ/ <li> Show the inherent /a/ explicitly </ul> The sample Pali text would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="laopali"> ເຍ ຘັມມາ ເຫຕຸປປະຠະວາ ເຕສັງ ເຫຕຸງ ຕະຖາຄະໂຕ ອາຫະ ຯ <br/> ເຕສັຎຈະ ໂຍ ນິໂຣໂຘ ເອວັງ ວາທີ ມະຫາສະມະໂຓ </span> <br/><br/><b> Sajjhaya Orthography </b> <br/>Applies the Thai Sajjhaya orthographic conventions to the Lao text. See the <a href="http://aksharamukha.appspot.com/describe/Thai">Thai script</a> page for more details. The sample Pali text above would be renderd as: <br/><br/><span class="laopali">ເຍ ຘັມ໌ມາ ເຫຕຸປ໌ປຠວາ ເຕສໍ ເຫຕຸໍ ຕຖາຄໂຕ ອາຫ ຯ <br/>ເຕສັຎ໌ຈ ໂຍ ນິໂຣໂຘ ເອວໍ ວາທີ ມຫາສມໂຓ ຯຯ</span><br/><br/><b>Sajjhaya Orthography (Nativized)</b><br/>This combines the features of Lao orthography and Sajjhaya orthography. Using this, the above text would be rendered as: <br/><br/><span class="laopali">ເຍ ຘັມ໌ມາ ເຫຕຸປ໌ປະຠະວາ ເຕສັງ ເຫຕຸງ ຕະຖາຄະໂຕ ອາຫະ ຯ<br/>ເຕສັຎ໌ຈະ ໂຍ ນິໂຣໂຘ ເອວັງ ວາທີ ມະຫາສະມະໂຓ ຯຯ</span><br/><br/><b>Lao Phonetic</b><br/>This replaces the following consonants with the equivalent phonetic counterpart. <br/><br/> ຄ → ກ, ຊ → ຈ, ທ → ດ, ພ → ບ, Niggahita → ງໍ',
        'Thai': '<b> Thai Digraphs </b> <br/>Thai considers certain CC sequences as digraphs and treats them as indivisible units. Thus, /dve/ is written as เทฺว as opposed to the usual ทฺเว, with ทฺว being a digraph. Aksharamukha follows the following rules of thumb to detect digraphs. <br/> <ul> <li> Word-inital clusters <li> Conjuncts with the semi-vowels ( /ya/, /va/, /ra/, /la/ ) in post-consonantal positions <li> Conjuncts of /h/ in both post-consonantal and pre-consonantal positions <li>Conjuncts of /s/ in pre-consonantal postions </ul> This digraph application is done by default to the output text. <br/> <br/><b> Thai Orthography </b> <br/>This applies the following conventions: <br/> <ul> <li> Replace Anusvara with /ṅ/ <li> Show the inherent /a/ explicitly <li> Digraphs are reversed </ul> The Sample pali text above would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="thai"> เย ธัมมา เหตุปปะภะวา เตสัง เหตุง ตะถาคะโต อาหะ ฯ <br/> เตสัญจะ โย นิโรโธ เอวัง วาที มะหาสะมะโณ ๚ </span> <br/><br/> <b> Sajjhāya Orthography </b> <br/>The <a href="https://www.sajjhaya.org/">Sajjhaya</a> edition of the Triptaaka uses a different kind of orthography. It follows the following conventions. <ul> <li> The Phinthu    ฺ  is replaced by Thanthakat     ์  (Except /ง/ which is shown without any marks). /kittī/: กิต์ตี</li> <li> Unless, the conjunct is combination of a varga (/ka/ to /ma/) and non-varga letter (/ya/ to /ha/), then it is replaced by Yamaka   ๎ and treat the sequence as a digraph. /dve/: เท๎ว, /brāhmaṇa/: พ๎ราห๎มณ </li> <li> Mark /a/ explicitly before conjuncts. /kamma/: กัม์ม (Except digraphs: /tatra/ ตต๎ร)</li></ul> For instance <br/><i>evaṃ me sutaṃ, ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bārāṇasiyaṃ viharati isipatane migadāye tatra kho bhagavā pañcavaggiye bhikkhū āmantesi: "dve me bhikkhave, antā pabbajitena na sevitabbā</i> <br/>เอวํ เม สุตํ, เอกํ สมยํ ภควา พาราณสิยํ วิหรติ อิสิปตเน มิคทาเย ตต๎ร โข ภควา ปัญ์จวัค์คิเย ภิก์ขู อามัน์เตสิ: "เท๎ว เม ภิก์ขเว, อัน์ตา ปัพ์พชิเตน น เสวิตัพ์พา<br/> <br/><b> Sajjhaya Orthography (Nativized)</b><br/> This combines the features of Thai orthography and Sajjhaya orthography. Using this, the above text would be rendered as: <br/>เอวัง เม สุตัง, เอกัง สะมะยัง ภะคะวา พาราณะสิยัง วิหะระติ อิสิปะตะเน มิคะทาเย ตะต๎ระ โข ภะคะวา ปัญ์จะวัค์คิเย ภิก์ขู อามัน์เตสิ: "เท๎ว เม ภิก์ขะเว, อัน์ตา ปัพ์พะชิเตนะ นะ เสวิตัพ์พา<br/><br/><b> Thai Phonetic </b><br/>Thai Phonetic follows phonetic Thai spelling as shown <a href="https://www.sajjhaya.org/node/101">here</a>. The following conventions are applied <ol><li>Inherent /a/ is explicitly displayed<li>/ga/ and /ja/ are shown as <span class="thainative">ก̥ </span> /ka/ with ring below and <span class="thainative">จ̥</span> /ca/ with ring below <li> /da/ & /ba/ are replaced by ด & บ <li> Anusvara and consonantal /ṅ/ is shown as งํ. /maṅgalaṃ/ : <span class="thainative">มังํก̥ะลังํ</span> <li> Conjuncts with /y/, /r/, /l/, /v/, /h/ are showing as a digraph with combining breve below. /dve/ : <span class="thainative">เด͜ว</span> <li> /h/-initial conjuncts are also shown with a combining breve. /brāhmaṇa/ : <span class="thainative">บ͜ราห͜มะณะ</span> <li> Vowels /e/, /o/ & /ā/ followed by a pure consonant is marked with the vowel shortener: Mai Tai Khu. /hontu/ : <span class="thainative">โห็นติ</span></ol> The above sample text would be rendered as below: <br/><span class="thainative">เอวังํ เม สุตังํ, เอกังํ สะมะยังํ ภะก̥ะวา บาราณะสิยังํ วิหะระติ อิสิปะตะเน มิก̥ะดาเย ตะต͜ระ โข ภะก̥ะวา ปัญจะวัก̥ก̥ิเย ภิกขู อามันเตสิ: "เด͜ว เม ภิกขะเว, อันตา ปับบะจ̥ิเตนะ นะ เสวิตับบา</span><br/><br/> A <a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/ThaiPaliRingBreve.otf">modified version</a> of Noto Serif Thai is used to render the Thai phonetic text.',
        'WarangCiti': '/h/ is sometimes used to denote vowel lengthening as in /ah/, /ih/ and /uh/. Given that the consonants have an inherent vowel and a functional Virama is not present, the lack of inherent vowel must be ascertained contextually (similar to Schwa deletion in Hindi). Likewise, consonantal clusters must also be read contextually.<br/><br/> <span class="warangciti">𑣄</span> is actually the glottal stop /ʔ/ but seems to be traditionally mapped to Visarga. The digraph <span class="warangciti">𑢹𑣗</span> is mapped to /v̈/ (v + nukta) <br/><br/> <b> Conservative Warang Citi </b><br/><br/> A form of conservative Warang Citi orthography used superscripted letters to indicate aspiration and conjuncts, thereby trying to compensate for the lack of a Virama. For instance, /ananta/ :: <span class="warangciti">𑣁𑣓𑣓‍𑣕</span> (as opposed to <span class="warangciti">𑣁𑣓𑣓𑣕</span>) or /ūṭṭuī/ <span class="warangciti">𑣇𑣒‍𑣒𑣃𑣆</span> (as opposed to <span class="warangciti">𑣇𑣒𑣒𑣃𑣆</span>). Without the visual clustering, the sequences could be read as /ananata/ (even /annata/ for that matter!) or /ūṭaṭauī/. The superscript just makes it explicit that the letters are to be read as a cluster. Similarly, aspirated consonants are shown using superscripted /h/, like /bha/ : <span class="warangciti">𑣗‍𑣙</span> and /cha/ : <span class="warangciti">𑣏‍𑣙</span>. Also, /ṃ/ is clustered with the previous vowel as in /aṃḍe/ : <span class="warangciti">𑣁‍𑣀𑣑𑣈</span>. The conservative orthography also used /ṣ/ : <span class="warangciti">𑣝</span>, whereas in modern orthography it would be simply replaced by /s/ : <span class="warangciti">𑣞</span>. <br/><br/>These are not enabled by default and only used when the <i>Preserve source</i> option is selected. Using this type of conservative orthography, the above Pali verse would be rendered as: <br/><br/> <span class="warangciti">𑣅𑣈 𑣔‍𑣙𑣖‍𑣖𑣁 𑣙𑣈𑣕𑣃𑣘‍𑣘𑣗‍𑣙𑣟𑣁 𑣕𑣈𑣞𑣀 𑣙𑣈𑣕𑣃‍𑣀 𑣕𑣕‍𑣙𑣁𑣋𑣕𑣉 𑣁𑣙𑣙 . <br/>𑣕𑣈𑣞𑣍‍𑣏 𑣅𑣉 𑣓𑣂𑣜𑣉𑣔‍𑣙𑣉 𑣈𑣟𑣀 𑣟𑣁𑣔𑣆 𑣖𑣙𑣁𑣞𑣖𑣐𑣉 ..</span> <br/><br/> <b>Remove word-final Schwa </b> <br/><br/> The word-final schwa /a/ is not usually pronounced in Warang Citi. This option removes the schwa /a/ in the output script. The above sample text with Schwa deltion would read as below: <br/><br/> hoo jagār do jārakaṃḍ, oḍisā, hasur saḥ baṅagāl re tīn 10 eeṃgel hoo jati ko aḥ leḥkaji tanā. ayār do hoo jagār īṅalis, deonāgari, oḍiyā, bāṅalā emān ko te oloḥ tīkenā, nāḥ do v̈āraṅ citi te ge oloḥ tanā. v̈āraṅ citi do hoo hudā ren mieḍ seṃyān hoo lako bodare bī leḍā. yunesako do nen jagār oṃḍoḥ cimineṅ sirame re do aḍoḥa menateḥ manātiṅ taḍā. nāḥ hoo jagār v̈āraṅ citi te vikipiiḍiyā bīyoḥ tanā, nānā menado aūri bī sekāḥoa, pīṭi sesen tanā. hoo te vikipiiḍiyā bī pīṭi re deṅagā em sanāṅ tan ko nen re bu otāyā. hoo jagār v̈āraṅ citi nitire lagiḍ tisiṅaḥ din re dorakarā ci onalāīn paleeṭapooram re lāḥ te lāḥ bu nitireyā.. <br/><br/> <b> Capitalization </b><br/><br/> Warang Citi is a bicameral script i.e. it has uppercase and lowercase letters. An option can be enabled to capitalize the Warang Citi output contextually.',
        'Gurmukhi': 'Addak is automatically used to mark gemination of consonants.  /pakkī/ : ਪੱਕੀ :: /pakkhī/ : ਪੱਖੀ. You can also enable an option to remove shwas that appear word finally. <br/><br/><b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Gurmukhi output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> Tippi is used to mark the gemination of /m/ and /n/ </li> <li> Contextual placement of Tippi & Bindu based on the preceding vowel.</li>',
        'Oriya': '<b> Nativization Conventions </b><br/><br/> The following nativization conventions are automatically applied to the Oriya output to increase readability. <br/> <ul> <li> /va/ is replaced by /ba/ at intervocalic positions.</li> <li> /y/ and /ẏ/ are contextually placed based on the following rules. /y/ is used word-intially. Otherise, /ẏ/ is used at intervocalic and post-consonantal positions.</li>',
        'Newa': 'Newa used \'Murmered \'Consonants in its reportoire. These are atomically encoded in Unicode. If you select enable murmered consonants, the sequences /hṅa/, /hña/, /hna/, /hma/ and /hra/ replaced by their atomic murmered equivalents <span class="newa">/𑐓/, /𑐙/, /𑐤/, /𑐪/ and /𑐭/</span> respectively. <br/><br/> Newa has two ways for forming r-initial conjuncts - one without repha /rka/: <span class="newa">𑐬𑑂‍𑐎</span> and one with repha /rka/: <span class="newa">𑐬𑑂𑐎</span>. Aksharamukha by default uses the repha-form, as it is the one used in Sanskrit texts. But this behavior can be changed by disabling the repha option. <br><br/> Newa also sometimes uses a special variant to form conjuncts of /ta/ usually before /ka/, /sa/ and /va/. <span class="newa">𑐟𑑂𑐎 𑐟𑑂𑐳 𑐟𑑂𑐰 </span> (normal) :: <span class="newa">𑐟𑑂‍𑐎 𑐟𑑂‍𑐳 𑐟𑑂‍𑐰</span> (special). This can also be optionally enabled and it will form this special form for all conjuncts with initial /ta/. <br/><br/>  This Noto Sans Newa has few issues and may not display some conjuncts properly, in those cases you may want to use an alternate devanagar-encoded Newa font. It can be downloaded from <a href="https://github.com/virtualvinodh/aksharamukha/blob/master/aksharamukha-front/src/statics/Nepal-lipi.ttf">here</a>.',
        'Ranjana': 'Ranjana is not yet encoded in Unicode. As a result, all of the existing fonts are either legacy 8-bit fonts or Unicode fonts that have been hack-eenocded to Devanagari or Tibetan.  Aksharamukkha uses a Devanagari-encoded Ranjana font as the default. In the absence of this font, the text will appear as plain Devanagari. <br/><br/> Ranjana being a pan-Indic script has several styles. There are two Tibetan styles, Lantsa and Wartu. These can be selected by enabling the respective option in the converter. These Tibetan-style fonts have been encoded in Tibetan Unicode and can be download from <a href="http://sonamdawa.com/download/#elf_l1_VGliZXRhbiBGb250cyAoVU5JQ09ERSkvTGFudHNhIGFuZCBXYXJ0dQ" target="_blank">here</a>. <br/><br> None of the fonts are perfect. Some complex ligatures like /trya/ etc. are better supported by the tibetan-style fonts rather than the default one. Please choose the font that displays your text the best.',
        'Wancho': '<b> Wancho Tones </b> <br><br/> Wancho tones can be formed as follows: ka\\_ ka\\- ka\\! ka\\; :: <span class="wancho">𞋔𞋁𞋬 𞋔𞋁𞋭 𞋔𞋁𞋮 𞋔𞋁𞋯</span> <br/><br/> <b> Wancho Nasalized Vowels </b> <br/><br/>The Wancho nasalized vowels <span class="wancho">𞋢 𞋣 𞋤 𞋥</span> are formed using the Anusvara as <i>oṃ āṃ aṃ iṃ</i> and the other set of vowels <span class="wancho">𞋦 𞋧 𞋨 𞋪</span> are formed using the Chandrbaindu as <i>om̐ em̐ ām̐ um̐</i>. Apart from these vowels, the Anusvara is mapped to /ṅ/ and the Chandrabindu to /n/. <br/><br/> <b> Special Consonants </b><br/><br/>The special consonants <span class="wancho">𞋡</span> /tr/ and <span class="wancho">𞋠</span> /ts/ are formed automatically from the sequences /tr/ and /ts/. And <span class="wancho">𞋒</span> /w/ as combination of /v/ and Nukta: /v̈/.',
        'Mro': '<b> Additional Consonants </b><br/>The additional Mro consonants for /k/, /l/ and /m/ can be accessed by appending numerals as shown below: <ul> <li>m2 : <span class="mro">𖩎</span><li>k2 : <span class="mro">𖩙</span><li>l2 : <span class="mro">𖩚</span><li> l3 : <span class="mro">𖩛</span><li>h2 : <span class="mro">𖩜</span><li>t2 : <span class="mro">𖩞</span>',
